>>VALLEE: We don't know.

00:50:53.270 --> 00:50:56.470 align:middle line:84%
But one of the most
interesting things

00:50:56.470 --> 00:51:03.520 align:middle line:84%
is that she talks about the heat
being transmitted through that.

00:51:03.520 --> 00:51:07.210 align:middle line:84%
So that you could apply it
to your skin when it was hot.

00:51:07.210 --> 00:51:09.730 align:middle line:84%
And I can testify,
it gets really

00:51:09.730 --> 00:51:12.220 align:middle line:84%
hot in New Mexico in
the middle of August,

00:51:12.220 --> 00:51:13.480 align:middle line:90%
because I've been there.

00:51:13.480 --> 00:51:17.303 align:middle line:84%
And you could put it to your
skin and it would stay cool.

00:51:17.303 --> 00:51:18.970 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That metal,
that memory metal.

00:51:18.970 --> 00:51:19.760 align:middle line:90%
Yes, it didn't--

00:51:19.760 --> 00:51:20.850 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: The metal
would not warm up.

00:51:20.850 --> 00:51:21.370 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That's right.

00:51:21.370 --> 00:51:21.870 align:middle line:90%
>>VALLEE: OK?

00:51:21.870 --> 00:51:22.090 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:51:22.090 --> 00:51:23.530 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: So my
physicist friends--

00:51:23.530 --> 00:51:24.460 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So she'd
put it on her cheeks,

00:51:24.460 --> 00:51:26.905 align:middle line:84%
because it felt cool in
the middle of the summer.

00:51:26.905 --> 00:51:27.760 align:middle line:90%
>>VALLEE: Yes.

00:51:27.760 --> 00:51:31.375 align:middle line:84%
My physics friends are very,
very interested in that.

00:51:31.375 --> 00:51:32.770 align:middle line:90%
How can you do that?

00:51:32.770 --> 00:51:36.130 align:middle line:84%
Why would they
transmit heat that way,

00:51:36.130 --> 00:51:38.260 align:middle line:84%
rather than warming
up the metal?

00:51:38.260 --> 00:51:39.430 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:51:39.430 --> 00:51:41.770 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: And what
is the structure?

00:51:41.770 --> 00:51:46.600 align:middle line:84%
What is the fine structure
of that substance?

00:51:46.600 --> 00:51:49.640 align:middle line:10%
>>HARRIS: But you were, I think,
referring to the fiber optics,

00:51:49.640 --> 00:51:50.440 align:middle line:10%
the--

00:51:50.440 --> 00:51:50.950 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:51:50.950 --> 00:51:53.080 align:middle line:84%
Thank you for the metals,
because we needed that part,

00:51:53.080 --> 00:51:53.275 align:middle line:90%
too.

00:51:53.275 --> 00:51:53.470 align:middle line:90%
But--

00:51:53.470 --> 00:51:54.520 align:middle line:90%
>>HARRIS: Yeah, the--

00:51:54.520 --> 00:51:55.300 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: The angel hair.

00:51:55.300 --> 00:51:56.258 align:middle line:90%
>>HARRIS: It might be--

00:51:56.258 --> 00:51:59.650 align:middle line:84%
the angel hair might
be fiber optics.

00:51:59.650 --> 00:52:01.870 align:middle line:84%
It might be a type
of fiber optic.

00:52:01.870 --> 00:52:06.910 align:middle line:84%
And whatever it was, they
collected 10-pound bag of it.

00:52:06.910 --> 00:52:07.900 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:52:07.900 --> 00:52:09.580 align:middle line:90%
OK, now let's move forward.

00:52:09.580 --> 00:52:13.780 align:middle line:84%
Because when you're
talking about fiber optics,

00:52:13.780 --> 00:52:16.300 align:middle line:90%
according to Philip Corso--

00:52:16.300 --> 00:52:17.560 align:middle line:90%
>>HARRIS: Corso, yes.

00:52:17.560 --> 00:52:17.860 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:52:17.860 --> 00:52:19.630 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: The same thing
comes into play here.

00:52:19.630 --> 00:52:19.840 align:middle line:90%
>>HARRIS: Yeah.

00:52:19.840 --> 00:52:21.070 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And in
this story, there's

00:52:21.070 --> 00:52:23.650 align:middle line:84%
another metal filing cabinet
in the military where stuff

00:52:23.650 --> 00:52:27.400 align:middle line:84%
is unpacked and looked at with
the intention of examining

00:52:27.400 --> 00:52:29.140 align:middle line:90%
and perhaps reverse engineering.

00:52:29.140 --> 00:52:31.660 align:middle line:84%
So I want to get to that
part of the story now.

00:52:31.660 --> 00:52:35.170 align:middle line:84%
So with all of this, and there's
so much more-- and Paola,

00:52:35.170 --> 00:52:36.970 align:middle line:84%
you did such a
good job out there,

00:52:36.970 --> 00:52:40.210 align:middle line:84%
because you were treating
them with such respect

00:52:40.210 --> 00:52:42.820 align:middle line:84%
and what they
deserved, rather than

00:52:42.820 --> 00:52:45.530 align:middle line:84%
the military coming around and
bullying them and overlooking

00:52:45.530 --> 00:52:46.330 align:middle line:90%
them.

00:52:46.330 --> 00:52:47.130 align:middle line:90%
Calling them out.

00:52:47.130 --> 00:52:48.920 align:middle line:84%
They're just a couple
Indian kids there.

00:52:48.920 --> 00:52:49.720 align:middle line:90%
Who cares?

00:52:49.720 --> 00:52:50.762 align:middle line:90%
They didn't see anything.

00:52:50.762 --> 00:52:53.300 align:middle line:84%
They're not-- they didn't
matter to anyone's life.

00:52:53.300 --> 00:52:55.190 align:middle line:84%
And it turns out, they
mattered the most.

00:52:55.190 --> 00:52:57.430 align:middle line:90%
So now we're past that part.

00:52:57.430 --> 00:53:00.010 align:middle line:84%
And I really recommend people
pick it up and read it.

00:53:00.010 --> 00:53:01.340 align:middle line:90%
I love this story.

00:53:01.340 --> 00:53:02.590 align:middle line:90%
I was glued to it.

00:53:02.590 --> 00:53:05.050 align:middle line:84%
Now let's go to your
feelings on the implications.

00:53:05.050 --> 00:53:07.870 align:middle line:90%
They took this away.

00:53:07.870 --> 00:53:10.180 align:middle line:84%
They took some of
probably the angel hair

00:53:10.180 --> 00:53:11.890 align:middle line:90%
and the metals and such away.

00:53:11.890 --> 00:53:13.540 align:middle line:90%
You have the bracket.

00:53:13.540 --> 00:53:14.570 align:middle line:90%
You got it from Reme.

00:53:14.570 --> 00:53:15.520 align:middle line:90%
You've got it now.

00:53:15.520 --> 00:53:18.160 align:middle line:84%
And it's somewhere else, so
don't go looking in your homes.

00:53:18.160 --> 00:53:22.120 align:middle line:84%
What do you think the state
of military back engineering

00:53:22.120 --> 00:53:25.210 align:middle line:84%
of this kind of
captured technology--

00:53:25.210 --> 00:53:26.950 align:middle line:90%
what state is it really in?

00:53:26.950 --> 00:53:31.810 align:middle line:84%
How much do you think has really
come of it through the years?

00:53:31.810 --> 00:53:34.240 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: I'm glad you asked
that, because that's really

00:53:34.240 --> 00:53:36.280 align:middle line:90%
the key question.

00:53:36.280 --> 00:53:40.690 align:middle line:84%
If Congress really wants to
ask a question, which I'm not

00:53:40.690 --> 00:53:45.010 align:middle line:84%
sure they do, but if they
want to ask a question,

00:53:45.010 --> 00:53:48.790 align:middle line:84%
the key question is, how
much longer are we going

00:53:48.790 --> 00:53:51.500 align:middle line:90%
to keep this beyond top secret?

00:53:51.500 --> 00:53:52.900 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:53:52.900 --> 00:53:53.860 align:middle line:90%
>>VALLEE: Beyond.

00:53:53.860 --> 00:53:57.050 align:middle line:84%
And I've worked
along in my career,

00:53:57.050 --> 00:54:00.625 align:middle line:84%
both in science and
in venture capital

00:54:00.625 --> 00:54:03.850 align:middle line:84%
and so on with people
who had high clearances.

00:54:03.850 --> 00:54:05.600 align:middle line:84%
They didn't know
anything about this.

00:54:05.600 --> 00:54:06.400 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:54:06.400 --> 00:54:07.300 align:middle line:90%
>>VALLEE: Why?

00:54:07.300 --> 00:54:10.720 align:middle line:84%
Well, because they had
the wrong clearances.

00:54:10.720 --> 00:54:13.840 align:middle line:84%
There are three different
systems of clearances

00:54:13.840 --> 00:54:15.970 align:middle line:90%
in the US government.

00:54:15.970 --> 00:54:19.630 align:middle line:84%
One system goes to
the president through

00:54:19.630 --> 00:54:22.480 align:middle line:90%
the appropriate agencies.

00:54:22.480 --> 00:54:25.600 align:middle line:84%
One system is
foreign intelligence,

00:54:25.600 --> 00:54:29.350 align:middle line:84%
which only goes to
the State Department

00:54:29.350 --> 00:54:34.480 align:middle line:84%
and to the diplomatic services,
and gets properly reported,

00:54:34.480 --> 00:54:38.390 align:middle line:84%
if there is a need to, to
the level of the executive.

00:54:38.390 --> 00:54:39.190 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:54:39.190 --> 00:54:42.610 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: And then there
are the atomic clearances,

00:54:42.610 --> 00:54:43.997 align:middle line:90%
which are completely separate.

00:54:43.997 --> 00:54:46.330 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Those are the highest
clearances, aren't they?

00:54:46.330 --> 00:54:46.450 align:middle line:90%
Or--

00:54:46.450 --> 00:54:48.680 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: No, there are
very high clearances

00:54:48.680 --> 00:54:48.970 align:middle line:90%
in all three systems.

00:54:48.970 --> 00:54:50.260 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, I guess
you would be at all levels.

00:54:50.260 --> 00:54:51.082 align:middle line:90%
Sure, yeah.

00:54:51.082 --> 00:54:52.540 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: There
are clearances that

00:54:52.540 --> 00:54:58.690 align:middle line:84%
are so exquisite that only a few
people have the right to know.

00:54:58.690 --> 00:55:00.550 align:middle line:84%
Because having a
clearance doesn't give you

00:55:00.550 --> 00:55:02.920 align:middle line:84%
the right to know, so
you have to have both.

00:55:02.920 --> 00:55:05.440 align:middle line:84%
You have to carry the
card, and then somebody

00:55:05.440 --> 00:55:08.080 align:middle line:84%
has to decide that
you should know

00:55:08.080 --> 00:55:10.880 align:middle line:84%
about this particular
secret that you're already

00:55:10.880 --> 00:55:11.680 align:middle line:90%
cleared for.

00:55:11.680 --> 00:55:12.760 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Mm-hmm.

00:55:12.760 --> 00:55:14.200 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: You have
the ticket, OK?

00:55:14.200 --> 00:55:15.000 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:17.050 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: But they won't
necessarily tell you.

00:55:17.050 --> 00:55:20.020 align:middle line:84%
And you might not-- the
code word might not be open,

00:55:20.020 --> 00:55:22.570 align:middle line:90%
might not be available.

00:55:22.570 --> 00:55:26.890 align:middle line:84%
On the atomic side,
which this is,

00:55:26.890 --> 00:55:30.790 align:middle line:84%
there are clearances
called R, P, and Q.

00:55:30.790 --> 00:55:32.620 align:middle line:84%
You know minding
your P's and Q's?

00:55:32.620 --> 00:55:34.858 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Mm-hmm.

00:55:34.858 --> 00:55:36.770 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: That are
the atomic secrets.

00:55:36.770 --> 00:55:37.570 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Mm-hmm.

00:55:37.570 --> 00:55:40.060 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: And those
would be the secrets

00:55:40.060 --> 00:55:43.870 align:middle line:84%
that people had at Los Alamos,
the secrets that are still

00:55:43.870 --> 00:55:46.930 align:middle line:84%
in existence about the
atomic bomb and about

00:55:46.930 --> 00:55:49.870 align:middle line:90%
the nuclear developments.

00:55:49.870 --> 00:55:53.290 align:middle line:84%
Those go through a
completely separate channel,

00:55:53.290 --> 00:55:56.080 align:middle line:84%
and they don't go to the
White House, unless there

00:55:56.080 --> 00:56:01.510 align:middle line:84%
is a need at that particular
point in current affairs

00:56:01.510 --> 00:56:09.040 align:middle line:84%
or in history for that to be
presented to the executive.

00:56:09.040 --> 00:56:10.810 align:middle line:90%
Because otherwise, you cannot--

00:56:10.810 --> 00:56:14.170 align:middle line:84%
number, one you cannot have a
lot of people knowing about it.

00:56:14.170 --> 00:56:17.290 align:middle line:84%
And also, the people
would not know

00:56:17.290 --> 00:56:20.350 align:middle line:84%
under what circumstances
this should

00:56:20.350 --> 00:56:25.700 align:middle line:84%
get the attention of the White
House and of the executive.

00:56:25.700 --> 00:56:28.870 align:middle line:84%
So there are-- all those
things are appropriate,

00:56:28.870 --> 00:56:33.260 align:middle line:84%
appropriate, boundaries
to the secret.

00:56:33.260 --> 00:56:34.060 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:56:34.060 --> 00:56:35.870 align:middle line:84%
I was going to try
to find, in fact,

00:56:35.870 --> 00:56:38.717 align:middle line:84%
a quote on exactly this,
that you put in the book.

00:56:38.717 --> 00:56:41.050 align:middle line:84%
And I thought I had written
the page down, but I hadn't.

00:56:41.050 --> 00:56:43.720 align:middle line:84%
But I remember,
basically, what it says.

00:56:43.720 --> 00:56:45.490 align:middle line:84%
And it says, you
have to remember

00:56:45.490 --> 00:56:50.860 align:middle line:84%
that these same documents are
going to be analyzed and taken

00:56:50.860 --> 00:56:53.620 align:middle line:84%
to the same people who have
covered this up for the last 75

00:56:53.620 --> 00:56:53.980 align:middle line:90%
years.

00:56:53.980 --> 00:56:55.595 align:middle line:84%
And they can spin it
any way they want.

00:56:55.595 --> 00:56:56.395 align:middle line:90%
>>VALLEE: Yes.

00:56:56.395 --> 00:56:59.350 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Same dossiers go to
the same agencies, and it's--

00:56:59.350 --> 00:57:00.343 align:middle line:90%
when does this end?

00:57:00.343 --> 00:57:01.510 align:middle line:90%
>>VALLEE: And I don't have--

00:57:01.510 --> 00:57:03.200 align:middle line:90%
I am not a whistleblower.

00:57:03.200 --> 00:57:04.000 align:middle line:90%
I'm not.

00:57:04.000 --> 00:57:05.842 align:middle line:84%
I'm a very
disciplined scientist.

00:57:05.842 --> 00:57:06.800 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes, you are.

00:57:06.800 --> 00:57:08.050 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: People
will tell you I am.

00:57:08.050 --> 00:57:08.190 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:57:08.190 --> 00:57:09.815 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, you're not a
conspiracy theorist.

00:57:09.815 --> 00:57:10.760 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:57:10.760 --> 00:57:11.310 align:middle line:90%


00:57:11.310 --> 00:57:13.060 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: That's why
I'm in Silicon Valley

00:57:13.060 --> 00:57:14.245 align:middle line:90%
and I work with teams.

00:57:14.245 --> 00:57:14.680 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:57:14.680 --> 00:57:16.240 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: I love to
be a team member.

00:57:16.240 --> 00:57:19.990 align:middle line:84%
I know what I can bring, and
I know what I don't know.

00:57:19.990 --> 00:57:22.510 align:middle line:90%
But the problem with--

00:57:22.510 --> 00:57:25.390 align:middle line:84%
and the secrecy
probably was appropriate

00:57:25.390 --> 00:57:27.550 align:middle line:90%
during the Cold War, OK?

00:57:27.550 --> 00:57:30.340 align:middle line:84%
It had to be in somebody's
basement in some out-of-the-way

00:57:30.340 --> 00:57:32.500 align:middle line:90%
place nobody talks about it.

00:57:32.500 --> 00:57:35.740 align:middle line:90%
But we've emerged from that.

00:57:35.740 --> 00:57:38.230 align:middle line:90%
We're in a different era now.

00:57:38.230 --> 00:57:41.920 align:middle line:84%
We're in an era
of where the Earth

00:57:41.920 --> 00:57:45.740 align:middle line:84%
itself is in trouble,
all over the place.

00:57:45.740 --> 00:57:50.110 align:middle line:84%
We need cooperation, and we need
to get the scientific community

00:57:50.110 --> 00:57:50.910 align:middle line:90%
involved.

00:57:50.910 --> 00:57:53.260 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: We need clean,
effective technology and energy

00:57:53.260 --> 00:57:54.430 align:middle line:90%
production, just to start.

00:57:54.430 --> 00:57:56.440 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: Well, with
secret technology,

00:57:56.440 --> 00:58:01.630 align:middle line:84%
if you find, say, a prototype
from China somewhere,

00:58:01.630 --> 00:58:05.350 align:middle line:84%
suppose that Tic Tacs are
from China and we get one.

00:58:05.350 --> 00:58:08.050 align:middle line:90%
We catch one.

00:58:08.050 --> 00:58:10.660 align:middle line:84%
It's going to be
taken apart, and it's

00:58:10.660 --> 00:58:14.005 align:middle line:84%
going to be given to different
teams and different companies.

00:58:14.005 --> 00:58:14.890 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:58:14.890 --> 00:58:18.100 align:middle line:90%
>>VALLEE: Lucky, Boeing, and IT.

00:58:18.100 --> 00:58:20.560 align:middle line:84%
IBM will look at
different things.

00:58:20.560 --> 00:58:22.450 align:middle line:84%
The people looking
at the control system

00:58:22.450 --> 00:58:25.450 align:middle line:84%
are not the people who are
going to look at the propulsion.

00:58:25.450 --> 00:58:26.320 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:58:26.320 --> 00:58:30.710 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: And they may not
know that the other labs exist,

00:58:30.710 --> 00:58:33.880 align:middle line:84%
and that's the way it has to
be to preserve the secrets.

00:58:33.880 --> 00:58:35.708 align:middle line:84%
It's compartmentalization
is and--

00:58:35.708 --> 00:58:37.000 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: But when is it ready?

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:40.110 align:middle line:84%
When does it no longer
need to be secret?

00:58:40.110 --> 00:58:41.860 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: But you're
not going to find out

00:58:41.860 --> 00:58:44.660 align:middle line:84%
what it does until these
people can talk to each other.

00:58:44.660 --> 00:58:45.460 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Exactly.

00:58:45.460 --> 00:58:47.860 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: But there are--
it's illegal for them

00:58:47.860 --> 00:58:48.840 align:middle line:90%
to talk to each other.

00:58:48.840 --> 00:58:49.640 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: [SIGHS]

00:58:49.640 --> 00:58:49.690 align:middle line:90%
>>HARRIS: [LAUGHS]

00:58:49.690 --> 00:58:50.750 align:middle line:90%
>>VALLEE: We need to stop that.

00:58:50.750 --> 00:58:51.958 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: We need to stop it.

00:58:51.958 --> 00:58:55.040 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: Somebody in Washington
needs to say, enough of that.

00:58:55.040 --> 00:58:55.840 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:58:55.840 --> 00:58:58.870 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: The scientific
community knows.

00:58:58.870 --> 00:59:00.970 align:middle line:84%
We think scientists
are skeptics and so on.

00:59:00.970 --> 00:59:03.622 align:middle line:90%
That's not true.

00:59:03.622 --> 00:59:05.440 align:middle line:84%
If you go to the
right level, you'll

00:59:05.440 --> 00:59:08.540 align:middle line:84%
have a very interesting
conversation about UFOs.

00:59:08.540 --> 00:59:09.340 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Mm-hmm.

00:59:09.340 --> 00:59:09.730 align:middle line:90%
>>VALLEE: OK?

00:59:09.730 --> 00:59:10.530 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:59:10.530 --> 00:59:13.240 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: And you'll find that
people have educated themselves

00:59:13.240 --> 00:59:15.940 align:middle line:84%
about it, and that they have
the same questions we're

00:59:15.940 --> 00:59:18.620 align:middle line:90%
discussing here, between us.

00:59:18.620 --> 00:59:22.510 align:middle line:10%
And have no problem in Silicon
Valley recruiting people

00:59:22.510 --> 00:59:23.885 align:middle line:10%
to come look at
this bracket, OK?

00:59:23.885 --> 00:59:24.685 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Mm-hmm.

00:59:24.685 --> 00:59:25.720 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:59:25.720 --> 00:59:26.410 align:middle line:90%
They wanted to see the bracket.

00:59:26.410 --> 00:59:27.370 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: When you
put it on the table,

00:59:27.370 --> 00:59:29.260 align:middle line:84%
and everybody has a
different opinion.

00:59:29.260 --> 00:59:30.800 align:middle line:90%
And that's where we start from.

00:59:30.800 --> 00:59:31.600 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:59:31.600 --> 00:59:34.970 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: Again, Federico Faggin
saying, if we stop doing this,

00:59:34.970 --> 00:59:37.097 align:middle line:84%
we might as well
disband Silicon Valley.

00:59:37.097 --> 00:59:37.930 align:middle line:90%
Everybody goes home.

00:59:37.930 --> 00:59:38.410 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Exactly.

00:59:38.410 --> 00:59:40.510 align:middle line:84%
Well, you two have done
such a beautiful job

00:59:40.510 --> 00:59:41.830 align:middle line:90%
constructing this.

00:59:41.830 --> 00:59:44.530 align:middle line:84%
And as we say, the science
may not be settled.

00:59:44.530 --> 00:59:45.700 align:middle line:90%
It may be continuing.

00:59:45.700 --> 00:59:47.740 align:middle line:84%
The exploration is
going to continue.

00:59:47.740 --> 00:59:50.230 align:middle line:84%
And what you said, is
absolutely critical.

00:59:50.230 --> 00:59:53.380 align:middle line:10%
That if we can't start
allowing these entities to talk

00:59:53.380 --> 00:59:55.480 align:middle line:10%
to one another, and to
reveal what we really have,

00:59:55.480 --> 00:59:57.580 align:middle line:10%
and what the potential
for humanity,

00:59:57.580 --> 01:00:00.130 align:middle line:10%
for our Earth is,
then what's the point?

01:00:00.130 --> 01:00:01.780 align:middle line:84%
It's getting-- to
this point, it's

01:00:01.780 --> 01:00:04.720 align:middle line:84%
becoming gratuitous to
keep it a secret anymore.

01:00:04.720 --> 01:00:08.020 align:middle line:84%
And I'm just so grateful
that you two came together

01:00:08.020 --> 01:00:10.540 align:middle line:84%
to do this, because there's
so much heart and warmth.

01:00:10.540 --> 01:00:13.750 align:middle line:84%
And I have to tell you, for a
techie scientist kind of guy,

01:00:13.750 --> 01:00:15.830 align:middle line:84%
what an elegant,
beautiful writer you are.

01:00:15.830 --> 01:00:16.630 align:middle line:90%
>>HARRIS: He is.

01:00:16.630 --> 01:00:17.050 align:middle line:90%
He is.

01:00:17.050 --> 01:00:17.625 align:middle line:90%
He actually--

01:00:17.625 --> 01:00:18.792 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: A stunning writer.

01:00:18.792 --> 01:00:20.390 align:middle line:84%
And this is your
second language.

01:00:20.390 --> 01:00:20.720 align:middle line:90%
>>HARRIS: Yes!

01:00:20.720 --> 01:00:21.122 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

01:00:21.122 --> 01:00:21.524 align:middle line:90%
This is--

01:00:21.524 --> 01:00:22.435 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: I am so impressed.

01:00:22.435 --> 01:00:24.010 align:middle line:84%
So anyway, I highly
recommend it.

01:00:24.010 --> 01:00:24.250 align:middle line:90%
>>HARRIS: Yes.

01:00:24.250 --> 01:00:25.375 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: A quick question.

01:00:25.375 --> 01:00:28.360 align:middle line:84%
First of all, did you like
the treatment of yourself

01:00:28.360 --> 01:00:30.652 align:middle line:84%
as a character in "Close
Encounters of the Third Kind"?

01:00:30.652 --> 01:00:31.452 align:middle line:90%
>>VALLEE: Well--

01:00:31.452 --> 01:00:32.997 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Were you OK with it?

01:00:32.997 --> 01:00:33.991 align:middle line:90%
>>VALLEE: Um--

01:00:33.991 --> 01:00:35.440 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

01:00:35.440 --> 01:00:37.065 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Sorry to
put you on the spot.

01:00:37.065 --> 01:00:40.780 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: It was-- I have a lot
of respect for Mr. Spielberg

01:00:40.780 --> 01:00:41.680 align:middle line:90%
and what he did.

01:00:41.680 --> 01:00:46.630 align:middle line:84%
He's the only-- really,
the only one in Hollywood

01:00:46.630 --> 01:00:51.293 align:middle line:84%
who understood the
human aspect of this.

01:00:51.293 --> 01:00:52.335 align:middle line:90%
It's not just technology.

01:00:52.335 --> 01:00:53.110 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: No, it's human.

01:00:53.110 --> 01:00:54.318 align:middle line:90%
>>VALLEE: Something shows up.

01:00:54.318 --> 01:00:55.420 align:middle line:90%
We get afraid.

01:00:55.420 --> 01:00:57.370 align:middle line:90%
We start shooting it.

01:00:57.370 --> 01:01:01.390 align:middle line:84%
The usual shoot
'em up alien film.

01:01:01.390 --> 01:01:03.130 align:middle line:84%
He understood what
was behind it.

01:01:03.130 --> 01:01:06.527 align:middle line:84%
And the idea of getting
Francois Truffaut was--

01:01:06.527 --> 01:01:07.360 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: I love it.

01:01:07.360 --> 01:01:08.330 align:middle line:90%
>>VALLEE: --was--

01:01:08.330 --> 01:01:08.830 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It was--

01:01:08.830 --> 01:01:09.460 align:middle line:90%
I love it.

01:01:09.460 --> 01:01:10.877 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: I have
a lot of respect,

01:01:10.877 --> 01:01:13.367 align:middle line:84%
coming from France,
for his movies.

01:01:13.367 --> 01:01:14.200 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: I love it.

01:01:14.200 --> 01:01:15.700 align:middle line:90%
I thought it was wonderful.

01:01:15.700 --> 01:01:17.367 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: And there
is a sense of humor.

01:01:17.367 --> 01:01:23.650 align:middle line:84%
One thing I'm very proud of
is that the sequence where

01:01:23.650 --> 01:01:28.390 align:middle line:84%
they steal the globe
from the-- well,

01:01:28.390 --> 01:01:31.030 align:middle line:84%
that that's something that's
an anecdote that I told

01:01:31.030 --> 01:01:36.340 align:middle line:84%
Spielberg when we had lunch
one day, about something

01:01:36.340 --> 01:01:38.720 align:middle line:84%
that happened when
Sputnik was launched.

01:01:38.720 --> 01:01:42.280 align:middle line:84%
There was-- nobody had a
computer program in the US

01:01:42.280 --> 01:01:45.050 align:middle line:84%
to compute an orbit of a
satellite of the Earth.

01:01:45.050 --> 01:01:45.850 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

01:01:45.850 --> 01:01:47.350 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: You could
compute an orbit

01:01:47.350 --> 01:01:50.350 align:middle line:84%
of the satellite of
Jupiter or something

01:01:50.350 --> 01:01:52.270 align:middle line:90%
like that, but not of the Earth.

01:01:52.270 --> 01:01:56.710 align:middle line:84%
So they had to take a globe
and put a piece of string

01:01:56.710 --> 01:02:00.310 align:middle line:84%
around the globe to
see where the Sputnik

01:02:00.310 --> 01:02:01.930 align:middle line:90%
1 was going to go next.

01:02:01.930 --> 01:02:03.537 align:middle line:84%
And Dr. Hynek was
involved in that.

01:02:03.537 --> 01:02:04.370 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: I love it.

01:02:04.370 --> 01:02:05.745 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: And he
had the picture.

01:02:05.745 --> 01:02:07.450 align:middle line:84%
And I told that
story to Spielberg.

01:02:07.450 --> 01:02:09.050 align:middle line:90%
And he said, that's it.

01:02:09.050 --> 01:02:09.850 align:middle line:90%
That's it.

01:02:09.850 --> 01:02:12.530 align:middle line:84%
They say, we've got a billion
dollars worth of technology

01:02:12.530 --> 01:02:13.330 align:middle line:90%
here.

01:02:13.330 --> 01:02:14.170 align:middle line:90%
It's all secret.

01:02:14.170 --> 01:02:15.490 align:middle line:90%
It's all classified.

01:02:15.490 --> 01:02:19.160 align:middle line:90%
And nobody has a map of Wyoming?

01:02:19.160 --> 01:02:19.960 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

01:02:19.960 --> 01:02:21.700 align:middle line:90%
And get me a map of Wyoming.

01:02:21.700 --> 01:02:23.820 align:middle line:90%
And they steal that globe.

01:02:23.820 --> 01:02:26.828 align:middle line:10%
That whole thing was one of the
funny parts in the movie, so--

01:02:26.828 --> 01:02:28.870 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: Oh, thank you
for sharing that with us.

01:02:28.870 --> 01:02:29.110 align:middle line:90%
>>VALLEE: So that was funny.

01:02:29.110 --> 01:02:29.620 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: I love it.

01:02:29.620 --> 01:02:29.635 align:middle line:90%
Well--

01:02:29.635 --> 01:02:30.850 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: I never
got paid for that.

01:02:30.850 --> 01:02:31.650 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

01:02:31.650 --> 01:02:32.840 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Well, that's OK.

01:02:32.840 --> 01:02:34.320 align:middle line:90%
You got paid in other ways, OK?

01:02:34.320 --> 01:02:34.675 align:middle line:90%
>>VALLEE: Yeah, but--

01:02:34.675 --> 01:02:35.475 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

01:02:35.475 --> 01:02:37.130 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: You get
to live with that.

01:02:37.130 --> 01:02:38.630 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: No, that
was a lot of fun.

01:02:38.630 --> 01:02:39.840 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh, I love it.

01:02:39.840 --> 01:02:40.280 align:middle line:90%
And--

01:02:40.280 --> 01:02:42.155 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: And there is
a fun element in that.

01:02:42.155 --> 01:02:44.270 align:middle line:84%
There is a fun
element in learning.

01:02:44.270 --> 01:02:46.850 align:middle line:90%
And I'm still learning.

01:02:46.850 --> 01:02:48.350 align:middle line:84%
I didn't know much
about the history

01:02:48.350 --> 01:02:50.970 align:middle line:90%
of World War II in the Pacific.

01:02:50.970 --> 01:02:53.430 align:middle line:84%
And I knew the
history in Europe.

01:02:53.430 --> 01:02:54.230 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

01:02:54.230 --> 01:02:56.355 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: I didn't know
the history in the Pacific,

01:02:56.355 --> 01:02:59.270 align:middle line:84%
and there are some
incredible, incredible things.

01:02:59.270 --> 01:03:00.950 align:middle line:84%
And they are not
teaching in schools.

01:03:00.950 --> 01:03:01.420 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Not talked about.

01:03:01.420 --> 01:03:02.360 align:middle line:90%
No, they're not.

01:03:02.360 --> 01:03:05.100 align:middle line:10%
>>VALLEE: About the war,
the end of the war in Japan.

01:03:05.100 --> 01:03:05.900 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

01:03:05.900 --> 01:03:07.220 align:middle line:84%
>>VALLEE: And what
it did to Japan.

01:03:07.220 --> 01:03:07.850 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

01:03:07.850 --> 01:03:08.650 align:middle line:90%
Another show.

01:03:08.650 --> 01:03:09.772 align:middle line:90%
>>VALLEE: And what it was.

01:03:09.772 --> 01:03:10.730 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Another show.

01:03:10.730 --> 01:03:11.540 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

01:03:11.540 --> 01:03:15.200 align:middle line:84%
And kudos to you for
continuing to learn every day,

01:03:15.200 --> 01:03:16.490 align:middle line:90%
every breath of your life.

01:03:16.490 --> 01:03:19.530 align:middle line:84%
I very much have a
deep respect for that.

01:03:19.530 --> 01:03:21.140 align:middle line:84%
And same for you,
Paola, to go out

01:03:21.140 --> 01:03:24.320 align:middle line:84%
with such passion and heart,
and go out and get these stories

01:03:24.320 --> 01:03:25.220 align:middle line:90%
and bring them to us.

01:03:25.220 --> 01:03:27.282 align:middle line:84%
And bringing people
together like this.

01:03:27.282 --> 01:03:29.740 align:middle line:84%
Anything final you would like
to say before we say goodbye?

